{
  "title": "Apprenticeships in Austria",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ea9aabd9-dbda-4821-91b5-1d50be6b5901",
      "text": "Apprenticeship training in Austria is organized in a [[dual education system]]: company-based training of apprentices is complemented by compulsory attendance of a part-time vocational school for apprentices (Berufsschule).[http://www.bmukk.gv.at/enfr/school/secon/app.xml Archived copy] It lasts two to four years &ndash; the duration varies among the 250 legally recognized apprenticeship trades."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fc5907b0-ddc4-43df-83d5-f1c8d18d0237",
      "text": "About 40 percent of all Austrian teenagers enter apprenticeship training upon completion of compulsory education (at age 15). This number has been stable since the 1950s.[http://wko.at/statistik/jahrbuch/Lehrling5.pdf Archived copy]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d056b81a-6720-41df-a682-a69684b1e7e7",
      "text": "The five most popular trades are: Retail Salesperson (5,000 people complete this apprenticeship per year), Clerk (3,500 / year), Car Mechanic (2,000 / year), Hairdresser (1,700 / year), Cook (1,600 / year).[http://www.statistik.at/web_de/statistiken/soziales/gender-statistik/bildung/043955.html Bildung] There are many smaller trades with small numbers of apprentices, like \"EDV-Systemtechniker\" (Sysadmin) which is completed by fewer than 100 people a year."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f15a563d-0046-4b73-8327-2b325be80df3",
      "text": "The Apprenticeship Leave Certificate provides the apprentice with access to two different vocational careers. On the one hand, it is a prerequisite for the admission to the Master Craftsman Exam and for qualification tests, and on the other hand it gives access to higher education via the TVE-Exam or the Higher Education Entrance Exam which are prerequisites for taking up studies at colleges, universities, \"Fachhochschulen\", post-secondary courses and post-secondary colleges.<ref name=\"bmukk.gv.at\"/>"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "73428c01-d628-498a-9d4b-15d51cff43d0",
      "text": "The person responsible for overseeing the training inside the company is called \"Lehrherr\" or \"Ausbilder\". An Ausbilder must prove he has the professional qualifications needed to educate another person. The \"Ausbilder\" must also prove he does not have a criminal record and is an otherwise respectable person. According to the laws: ''the person wanting to educate a young apprentice must prove that he has an ethical way of living and the civic qualities of a good citizen''."
    }
  ],
